## §2 — What each component is, why it exists, tradeoffs

### SIP phone / softphone

**What:** The **endpoint** — a hardware desk phone, mobile app, or desktop app that speaks SIP and sends/receives RTP audio.  
**Why you need it:** Without endpoints there's nobody to call.  
**Tradeoff:** Hardware phones are **reliable** but costly; softphones are **free** but depend on OS audio stack and network quality.

### SIP carrier / PSTN gateway

**What:** The **other side's network** that connects your VoIP world to the traditional phone network (or another SIP network). They sell you **phone numbers (DIDs)** and **call capacity (channels, CPS)**.  
**Why you need it:** Without a carrier, you can only call other phones on your own system.  
**Tradeoff:** More carriers = **redundancy** but more **peering configs** to maintain. Each carrier has its own quirks (codec preferences, CLI rules, timers).

### SBC (Session Border Controller)

**What:** A **network edge device** that sits between your internal VoIP and the outside world. It enforces **security** (TLS, rate limits, fraud detection), **hides** your internal topology, and handles **interop** between different SIP implementations. Often works as a **B2BUA** (terminates one SIP dialog and creates a new one inward).  
**Why you need it:** Without it, your Kamailio/Asterisk is **directly exposed** to the Internet — every scanner, every malformed packet.  
**Without it:** You can survive without an SBC in **small/internal** deployments; Kamailio can do some edge security. But carrier-grade or multi-carrier setups almost always use one.  
**Tradeoff:** **Cost** (commercial SBCs are expensive) and **complexity** (another hop, another config) vs **security and interop** stability.

### Kamailio

**What:** A **SIP proxy, registrar, and router**. It handles SIP messages at **high scale**: thousands of registrations, INVITE routing, load balancing (dispatcher module), NAT-related header fixes, and peering with carriers.  
**Why you need it:** Asterisk alone can't handle **thousands of concurrent SIP registrations** efficiently. Kamailio is **lightweight** — it just moves SIP messages, it doesn't process audio.  
**Does NOT do:** IVR menus, voicemail, conferencing, music on hold — that's Asterisk.  
**Tradeoff:** Kamailio at the **edge** gives you **scale** and **security** but its config language is low-level (not friendly for call logic). Asterisk at the edge is **simpler** for small setups but **won't scale** for carrier loads.

### Asterisk

**What:** A **PBX and application server**. It runs **dialplans** (call routing logic), **IVR** menus, **queues**, voicemail, conferencing, and handles media (codec transcoding, recording).  
**Why you need it:** Someone has to run the **business logic** — ring this queue, play this prompt, record this call. Kamailio can't do that.  
**Does NOT do:** It's not designed to be the **first Internet-facing** SIP hop at scale — that's Kamailio/SBC territory.  
**Tradeoff:** Asterisk is **feature-rich** but **heavier** per session than Kamailio. For pure routing without app logic, Kamailio is better. For app logic, Asterisk (or FreeSWITCH) is needed.

### RTPengine

**What:** A **kernel-assisted RTP relay and SDP rewriter**, controlled by Kamailio (via the **ng** control protocol — not SIP). When a phone behind NAT advertises a **private** IP in its SDP, RTPengine **rewrites** that to a **public relay** address and forwards the audio packets.  
**Why you need it:** Without it, calls between NATed phones and carriers get **one-way audio or no audio** because the SDP addresses are unreachable.  
**Does NOT do:** Call routing, dialplan, business logic — it **only** handles media relay instructions from Kamailio.  
**Tradeoff:** **Kernel mode** = very fast forwarding (millions of packets/sec) but needs a **kernel module** that must be rebuilt on every kernel update. **Userspace mode** = simpler but slower under heavy load.

### Homer / SIPCAPTURE

**What:** A **SIP signaling visibility** platform. Agents on your SIP servers send **HEP** (Homer Encapsulation Protocol) copies of SIP messages to Homer's collector for **search, drill-down, and call-flow diagrams**.  
**Why you need it:** When troubleshooting, you need to see the **SIP ladder** (who sent what, when) across multiple nodes. Homer gives you this without manually running tcpdump everywhere.  
**Tradeoff:** Another service to run and retain data for; but without it, troubleshooting multi-hop SIP is **painful**.

### Prometheus + Grafana

**What:** **Metrics** collection (Prometheus scrapes HTTP endpoints) + **dashboards and alerts** (Grafana visualizes, Alertmanager fires).  
**Why you need it:** You want to know **before** users complain that a trunk is returning 503s, or that CPS is spiking, or that RTPengine is dropping packets.  
**Tradeoff:** Setup and maintenance cost; but without metrics you're **blind** until someone calls to say "phones are down."

### Twilio / Genesys

**What:** **External platforms** you integrate with.  
- **Twilio:** offers **SIP trunks** (carrier replacement) + **REST APIs** for programmatic call control. Two integration surfaces: **network** (trunk, certs, IP allowlist) + **software** (webhooks, API keys).  
- **Genesys:** contact center platform with **SIP Server** + **CTI/web** for agent desktops. SIP trunk integration is separate from the web/CTI integration.  
**Tradeoff:** CPaaS (Twilio) = **fast** to start, **per-minute cost**; traditional carrier = cheaper at scale but more **peering** work.

### PostgreSQL / MongoDB

**What:** **Databases** used for CDRs (call detail records), Kamailio location table (if DB-backed), configs.  
**Why:** You need to store call history, billing data, and sometimes registrar state.  
**Tradeoff:** **Not in the RTP path** — but if the DB is slow, **REGISTER** lookups or CDR writes can lag.

### Linux (Debian 12)

**What:** The **OS** running everything. Interfaces, routing tables, `nftables` firewall, kernel module for RTPengine, time sync — half of "voice bugs" are actually **Linux networking bugs**.  
**Why it matters for interviews:** If you can't explain `ip route`, `nftables`, `conntrack`, or `tcpdump`, you can't debug VoIP.

